This particular driver was very outgoing and friendly, greeting us several times during the evening and even wishing us a good night as we were leaving.

DSC_2846.jpg

We were walking along the LA River bike path, from one end of the Frogtown Artwalk to the other, when a car began to tentatively pull out onto the path, where no car belongs. (I don't know how he even got that far.) The driver looked stressed and wanted to know how to get on to the nearby freeway. Several of us assured him that he'd have to back up and try again.
The best part? The sign on the side of the car identifying it as belonging to a driving school. (There's no need to identify the school. We all have off days.)

This lizard was so obliging about posing because he was dead as a door nail, as far as I could tell. (Why would anything that normally runs so well, and was so close to good cover, fake it?) But what drops a plump lizard in its tracks like this? What killed him? Questions like this keep me from eating these things raw.

There was some beautiful, iridescent color in the scales. An echo shoes up if you look at larger versions of the image. Unfortunately the only SLR lens I had was the telephoto. I should had tried close-ups with my cell phone camera.

This photo must have been accidental....

Is it really a good idea for this guy to be hanging out under the Anaheim Street bridge? How long has he been there? (Maybe he accounts for some of the frantic fish behavior I've seen in the last few weeks!)

This is a vacant lot where signs are stored: the kind of signs used in street repair, for example, with the battery-powered, flashing lights on top--which is what's visible here. Apparently they can't be turned off; or maybe no one bothers to do so. In any case, here they sit, flashing on and off indefinitely, day and night.

A number of fish were making a doomed attempt to swim up the LA River channel. Why? Some tried swimming up the concrete apron, but with most of their bodies out of the water, could not get traction (or had too much). Others tried swimming up the channel in the middle, but could not overcome the current for long before stalling and washing backward.

"Life will find a way," interrupting the rusty geometry of a railroad bridge crossing the concrete expanse of the LA River--somewhere near the home of Farmer John sausage, I think.

This was a solo ride. Not being familiar with the area, not looking like prey seemed like a good idea. I never slowed down without good visibility in all directions.

Next time I go this way, maybe I'll bring a real camera to chronicle the ragged landscape--with film chosen to do an especially good job capturing the colors of rust.

I took this near the trail's apparent end, at Atlantic Avenue.

This seems to be the northernmost end of the LA River bike trail. Just a few more miles to downtown LA, once I puzzle it out on a map. I have this idea that I'd like to get some Japanese-style seafood curry or a bowl of ramen as big as my head in Little Tokyo, and then turn back toward Long Beach.

080209_15431.jpg

After 1500 miles or so on mis-matched tires, I had an expensive, glancing encounter with a sharp rock. After that, my tires matched again, for the first time in ages, and the bike was more photo-worthy.
